    {
      "pos": [
        556,
        587
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"blob\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Blob Storage"
    },
    {
      "content": "The word \"blob\" is short for \"Binary Large OBject\", and it describes exactly what a blob is: a collection of binary information.",
      "pos": [
        589,
        717
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Yet even though they're simple, blobs are quite useful.",
      "pos": [
        718,
        773
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Figure 1<ept id=\"p1\">](#Fig1)</ept> illustrates the basics of Azure Blob Storage.",
      "pos": [
        774,
        837
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        839,
        884
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"Fig1\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">![</ph>Diagram of Blobs<ph id=\"ph4\">][blobs]</ph>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 1: Azure Blob Storage stores binary data - blobs - in containers.",
      "pos": [
        889,
        961
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To use blobs, you first create an Azure <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>storage account<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        965,
        1023
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As part of this, you specify the Azure datacenter that will store the objects you create using this account.",
      "pos": [
        1024,
        1132
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Wherever it lives, each blob you create belongs to some container in your storage account.",
      "pos": [
        1133,
        1223
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To access a blob, an application provides a URL with the form:",
      "pos": [
        1224,
        1286
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1288,
        1380
      ],
      "content": "http://&amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>StorageAccount<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>&amp;gt;.blob.core.windows.net/&amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Container<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>&amp;gt;/&amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>BlobName<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept>&amp;gt;"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1382,
        1598
      ],
      "content": "&amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>StorageAccount<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>&amp;gt; is a unique identifier assigned when a new storage account is created, while &amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Container<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>&amp;gt; and &amp;lt;<bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>BlobName<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept>&amp;gt; are the names of a specific container and a blob within that container."
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure provides two different kinds of blobs.",
      "pos": [
        1601,
        1645
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The choices are:",
      "pos": [
        1646,
        1662
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Block<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> blobs, each of which can contain up to 200 gigabytes of data.",
      "pos": [
        1666,
        1735
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As its name suggests, a block blob is subdivided into some number of blocks.",
      "pos": [
        1736,
        1812
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a failure occurs while transferring a block blob, retransmission can resume with the most recent block rather than sending the entire blob again.",
      "pos": [
        1813,
        1961
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Block blobs are a quite general approach to storage, and they're the most commonly used blob type today.",
      "pos": [
        1962,
        2066
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Page<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> blobs, which can be as large at one terabyte each.",
      "pos": [
        2070,
        2127
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Page blobs are designed for random access, and so each one is divided into some number of pages.",
      "pos": [
        2128,
        2224
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An application is free to read and write individual pages at random in the blob.",
      "pos": [
        2225,
        2305
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Azure Virtual Machines, for example, VMs you create use page blobs as persistent storage for both OS disks and data disks.",
      "pos": [
        2306,
        2431
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Whether you choose block blobs or page blobs, applications can access blob data in several different ways.",
      "pos": [
        2433,
        2539
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The options include the following:",
      "pos": [
        2540,
        2574
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Directly through a RESTful (i.e., HTTP-based) access protocol.",
      "pos": [
        2578,
        2640
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Both Azure applications and external applications, including apps running on premises, can use this option.",
      "pos": [
        2641,
        2748
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using the Azure Storage Client library, which provides a more developer-friendly interface on top of the raw RESTful blob access protocol.",
      "pos": [
        2751,
        2889
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Once again, both Azure applications and external applications can access blobs using this library.",
      "pos": [
        2890,
        2988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using Azure drives, an option that lets an Azure application treat a page blob as a local drive with an NTFS file system.",
      "pos": [
        2991,
        3112
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To the application, the page blob looks like an ordinary Windows file system accessed using standard file I/O.",
      "pos": [
        3113,
        3223
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In fact, reads and writes are sent to the underlying page blob that implements the Azure Drive.",
      "pos": [
        3224,
        3319
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To guard against hardware failures and improve availability, every blob is replicated across three computers in an Azure datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        3322,
        3454
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Writing to a blob updates all three copies, so later reads won't see inconsistent results.",
      "pos": [
        3455,
        3545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also specify that a blob's data should be copied to another Azure datacenter in the same geo but at least 500 miles away.",
      "pos": [
        3546,
        3675
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This copying, called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>geo-replication<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, happens within a few minutes of an update to the blob, and it's useful for disaster recovery.",
      "pos": [
        3676,
        3809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Data in blobs can also be made available via the Azure <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Content Delivery Network (CDN)<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3811,
        3899
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By caching copies of blob data at dozens of servers around the world, the CDN can speed up access to information that's accessed repeatedly.",
      "pos": [
        3900,
        4040
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Simple as they are, blobs are the right choice in many situations.",
      "pos": [
        4043,
        4109
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Storing and streaming video and audio are obvious examples, as are backups and other kinds of data archiving.",
      "pos": [
        4110,
        4219
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developers can also use blobs to hold any kind of unstructured data they like.",
      "pos": [
        4220,
        4298
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Having a straightforward way to store and access binary data can be surprisingly useful.",
      "pos": [
        4299,
        4387
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4393,
        4449
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"dbinvm\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Running a DBMS in a Virtual Machine"
    },
    {
      "content": "Many applications today rely on some kind of database management system (DBMS).",
      "pos": [
        4451,
        4530
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Relational systems such as SQL Server are the most frequently used choice, but non-relational approaches, commonly known as <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>NoSQL<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> technologies, get more popular every day.",
      "pos": [
        4531,
        4704
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To let cloud applications use these data management options, Azure Virtual Machines allows you to run a DBMS (relational or NoSQL) in a VM.",
      "pos": [
        4705,
        4844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Figure 2<ept id=\"p1\">](#Fig2)</ept> shows how this looks with SQL Server.",
      "pos": [
        4845,
        4900
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4902,
        4977
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"Fig2\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">![</ph>Diagram of SQL Server in a Virtual Machine<ph id=\"ph4\">][SQLSvr-vm]</ph>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 2: Azure Virtual Machines allows running a DBMS in a VM, with persistence provided by blobs.",
      "pos": [
        4982,
        5081
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To both developers and database administrators, this scenario looks much like running the same software in their own datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        5085,
        5213
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the example shown here, for instance, nearly all of SQL Server's capabilities can be used, and you have full administrative access to the system.",
      "pos": [
        5214,
        5362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You also have the responsibility of managing the database server, of course, just as if it were running locally.",
      "pos": [
        5363,
        5475
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Figure 2<ept id=\"p1\">](#Fig2)</ept> shows, your databases appear to be stored on the local disk of the VM the server runs in.",
      "pos": [
        5477,
        5587
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Under the covers, however, each of those disks is written to an Azure blob.",
      "pos": [
        5588,
        5663
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "(It's similar to using a SAN in your own datacenter, with a blob acting much like a LUN.) As with any Azure blob, the data it contains is replicated three times within a datacenter and, if you request it, geo-replicated to another datacenter in the same region.",
      "pos": [
        5664,
        5925
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It's also possible to use options such as SQL Server database mirroring for improved reliability.",
      "pos": [
        5926,
        6023
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another way to use SQL Server in a VM is to create a hybrid application, where the data lives on Azure while the application logic runs on-premises.",
      "pos": [
        6026,
        6174
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, this might make sense when applications running in multiple locations or on various mobile devices must share the same data.",
      "pos": [
        6175,
        6312
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To make communication between the cloud database and on-premises logic simpler, an organization can use Azure Virtual Network to create a virtual private network (VPN) connection between an Azure datacenter and its own on-premises datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        6313,
        6555
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6561,
        6593
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"sqldb\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>SQL Database"
    },
    {
      "content": "For many people, running a DBMS in a VM is the first option that comes to mind for managing structured data in the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        6595,
        6716
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It's not the only choice, though, nor is it always the best choice.",
      "pos": [
        6717,
        6784
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In some cases, managing data using a Platform as a Service (PaaS) approach makes more sense.",
      "pos": [
        6785,
        6877
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure provides a PaaS technology called SQL Database that lets you do this for relational data.",
      "pos": [
        6878,
        6973
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Figure 3<ept id=\"p1\">](#Fig3)</ept> illustrates this option.",
      "pos": [
        6974,
        7016
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7019,
        7072
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"Fig3\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">![</ph>Diagram of SQL Database<ph id=\"ph4\">][SQL-db]</ph>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 3: SQL Database provides a shared PaaS relational storage service.",
      "pos": [
        7077,
        7150
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "SQL Database doesn't give each customer its own physical instance of SQL Server.",
      "pos": [
        7154,
        7234
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Instead, it provides a multi-tenant service, with a logical SQL Database server for each customer.",
      "pos": [
        7235,
        7333
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All customers share the compute and storage capacity that the service provides.",
      "pos": [
        7334,
        7413
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And as with Blob Storage, all data in SQL Database is stored on three separate computers within an Azure datacenter, giving your databases built-in high availability (HA).",
      "pos": [
        7414,
        7585
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To an application, SQL Database looks much like SQL Server.",
      "pos": [
        7587,
        7646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Applications can issue SQL queries against relational tables, use T-SQL stored procedures, and execute transactions across multiple tables.",
      "pos": [
        7647,
        7786
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And because applications access SQL Database using the Tabular Data Stream (TDS) protocol, the same protocol used to access SQL Server, they can work with data using Entity Framework, ADO.NET, JDBC, and other familiar data access interfaces.",
      "pos": [
        7787,
        8028
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But because SQL Database is a cloud service running in Azure data centers, you don't need to manage any of the system's physical aspects, such as disk usage.",
      "pos": [
        8031,
        8188
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You also don't need to worry about updating software or handling other low-level administrative tasks.",
      "pos": [
        8189,
        8291
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each customer organization still controls its own databases, of course, including their schemas and user logins, but many of the mundane administrative tasks are done for you.",
      "pos": [
        8292,
        8467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While SQL Database looks much like SQL Server to applications, it doesn't behave exactly the same as a DBMS running on a physical or virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        8470,
        8619
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because it runs on shared hardware, its performance will vary with the load placed on that hardware by all of its customers.",
      "pos": [
        8620,
        8744
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means that the performance of, say, a stored procedure in SQL Database might vary from one day to the next.",
      "pos": [
        8745,
        8857
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Today, SQL Database lets you create a database holding up to 150 gigabytes.",
      "pos": [
        8860,
        8935
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you need to work with larger databases, the service provides an option called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Federation<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8936,
        9030
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To do this, a database administrator creates two or more <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>federation members<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, each of which is a separate database with its own schema.",
      "pos": [
        9031,
        9167
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Data is spread across these members, something that's often referred to as <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>sharding<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, with each member assigned a unique <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>federation key<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9168,
        9307
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "An application issues SQL queries against this data by specifying the federation key that identifies the federation member the query should target.",
      "pos": [
        9308,
        9455
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This allows using a traditional relational approach with large amounts of data.",
      "pos": [
        9456,
        9535
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As always, there are trade-offs; neither queries nor transactions can span federation members, for instance.",
      "pos": [
        9536,
        9644
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But when a relational PaaS service is the best choice and these trade-offs are acceptable, using SQL Federation can be a good solution.",
      "pos": [
        9645,
        9780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "SQL Database can be used by applications running on Azure or elsewhere, such as in your on-premises datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        9782,
        9893
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This makes it useful for cloud applications that need relational data, as well as on-premises applications that can benefit from storing data in the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        9894,
        10049
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A mobile application might rely on SQL Database to manage shared relational data, for instance, as might an inventory application that runs at multiple dealers around the world.",
      "pos": [
        10050,
        10227
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Thinking about SQL Database raises an obvious (and important) issue: When should you run SQL Server in a VM, and when is SQL Database a better choice?",
      "pos": [
        10229,
        10379
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As usual, there are trade-offs, and so which approach is better depends on your requirements.",
      "pos": [
        10380,
        10473
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One simple way to think about it is to view SQL Database as being for new applications, while SQL Server in a VM is a better choice when you're moving an existing on-premises application to the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        10476,
        10676
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It can also be useful to look at this decision in a more fine-grained way, however.",
      "pos": [
        10677,
        10760
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, SQL Database is easier to use, since there's minimal setup and administration.",
      "pos": [
        10761,
        10852
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But running SQL Server in a VM can have more predictable performance - it's not a shared service - and it also supports larger non-federated databases than SQL Database.",
      "pos": [
        10853,
        11022
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Still, SQL Database provides built-in replication of both data and processing, effectively giving you a high-availability DBMS with very little work.",
      "pos": [
        11023,
        11172
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While SQL Server gives you more control and a somewhat broader set of options, SQL Database is simpler to set up and significantly less work to manage.",
      "pos": [
        11173,
        11324
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Finally, it's important to point out that SQL Database isn't the only PaaS data service available on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        11326,
        11433
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft partners provide other options as well.",
      "pos": [
        11434,
        11483
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, ClearDB offers a MySQL PaaS offering, while Cloudant sells a NoSQL option.",
      "pos": [
        11484,
        11571
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "PaaS data services are the right solution in many situations, and so this approach to data management is an important part of Azure.",
      "pos": [
        11572,
        11704
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11711,
        11747
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"datasync\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>SQL Data Sync"
    },
    {
      "content": "While SQL Database does maintain three copies of each database within a single Azure datacenter, it doesn't automatically replicate data between Azure datacenters.",
      "pos": [
        11749,
        11912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Instead, it provides SQL Data Sync, a service that you can use to do this.",
      "pos": [
        11913,
        11987
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Figure 4<ept id=\"p1\">](#Fig4)</ept> shows how this looks.",
      "pos": [
        11988,
        12027
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        12029,
        12089
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"Fig4\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">![</ph>Diagram of SQL data sync<ph id=\"ph4\">][SQL-datasync]</ph>"
    },
    {
      "content": "Figure 4: SQL Data Sync synchronizes data in SQL Database with data in other Azure and on-premises datacenters.",
      "pos": [
        12094,
        12205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As the diagram shows, SQL Data Sync can synchronize data across different locations.",
      "pos": [
        12209,
        12293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Suppose you're running an application in multiple Azure datacenters, for instance, with data stored in SQL Database.",
      "pos": [
        12294,
        12410
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use SQL Data Sync to keep that data synchronized.",
      "pos": [
        12411,
        12468
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "SQL Data Sync can also synchronize data between an Azure datacenter and an instance of SQL Server running in an on-premises datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        12469,
        12604
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This might be useful for maintaining both a local copy of data used by on-premises applications and a cloud copy used by applications running on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        12605,
        12756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And although it's not shown in the figure, SQL Data Sync can also be used to synchronize data between SQL Database and SQL Server running in a VM on Azure or elsewhere.",
      "pos": [
        12757,
        12925
      ]
    },
    {
